{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"debbb490-9695-491d-9854-9f746760d9df","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n---\n\n**Tips:**\n\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't on the container's PATH, use the full SDK path or build a debug image with the SDK.\n- For **always-on** diagnostics, set the env var `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` (it's on by default, but some hardened images disable it).\n- If you can't install tools inside the container, you can use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar container instead — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection without modifying the app container.\n- On Windows containers, `dotnet-trace` uses **EventPipe** (not ETW), so no host-level admin privileges are needed inside the container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cc1df19c-9549-4a40-ac55-17110ea7c4e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"7811:8A8EB:1CF177C:2037C79:69FA983A"},"id":"a5437d4d-89f9-4727-9a09-2e3ed6af0377","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:24:20.847Z","parentId":"b3db16df-6ea0-461d-b340-6cc5d5a95e52"}
